defaultThe Postal Services Act 2011 protects the high-quality Universal Service
default enjoyed by customers across the UK
default. Its protections would continue to apply following any sale of shares
default in Royal Mail
default. The protections include a uniform service
default to rural areas, to which Royal Mail must continue to deliver the same high-quality service or risk large fines.  It also protects specific services, such as the Articles for the Blind scheme, which provides free postal services to blind or partially sight
defaulted people.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Postal Services Act 2011 sets down the minimum requirements of the universal postal service in law. These minimum requirements include the collection of letters every Monday to Saturday and a delivery service at affordable prices in accorda
defaultnce with a uniform tariff throughout the UK.  The requirements are set out 
defaultin S
defaultection 31 of the Postal Services Act 2011.  Any change to these minimum requirements would require the approval of both houses of the UK Parliament. The requirements are:
